{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2725"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2725"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.36,0.21,0.26,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52906"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2725"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38295"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3498"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52906"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four hour history of sudden onset and rapidly worsening upper abdominal pain. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes and a work-related back injury sustained three weeks ago. His medications include metformin and regular use of diclofenac for his back pain. His back pain has been more severe recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he is morbidly obese, with a blood pressure of 115/80 mmHg, pulse rate 110/min, temperature 37.4\u00baC and respiratory rate 18/min. Because of his body habitus, abdominal examination is limited, but there is tenderness in the epigastrium and the rest of the abdomen appears to be soft.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum lactate","Erect and supine abdominal X-rays","Chest X-ray","Serum lipase","FAST scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thought that should be uppermost in the mind of the supervising practitioner is the clear possibility that this patient has a perforated peptic ulcer. The recent use of a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agent and the sudden onset of severe upper abdominal pain would support such a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe assessment of the morbidly obese patient can be difficult - particularly with regards to examination of the abdomen. Signs of peritoneal irritation are easily masked by the layers of fat. The first aim of an investigation should be to try and confirm the suspected diagnosis and look for free intraperitoneal gas - best seen under the diaphragms. Some form of imaging is required and whilst a CT scan might provide more definition, in practice a \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may be more easily available and so should be performed initially as it is quick and relatively sensitive for free gas under the diaphragm (Image 2). If positive for free gas - this man would be taken to theatre for laparotomy and patch repair.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a \u003Cstrong\u003EFAST scan\u003C/strong\u003E is frequently used in the assessment of a patient with an acute abdomen, a chest X-ray is more likely to provide the diagnosis in this instance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErect and supine abdominal X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E would be performed if small bowel obstruction was suspected - looking for dilated bowel loops and multiple air fluid levels. Erect abdominal X-rays may not include the diaphragm (Image 1) and as such, are unreliable when looking for free gas under the diaphragms. If a patient with a suspected perforation is being assessed radiologically for free intra-abdominal gas and they are too ill to be sat up for an erect film, then a lateral decubitus view may provide the information sought. However, in such circumstances, a CT abdomen would be more useful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lipase\u003C/strong\u003E would be sent for possible pancreatitis, however is less likely than peptic ulcer disease here. The pain associated with acute pancreatitis is usually more gradual in onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lactate\u003C/strong\u003E estimation might be considered if it was thought that there was an ischaemic element to the patient\u0027s underlying problem - but that is very unlikely to be the case in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An erect chest X-ray is an easy and valuable tool for assessing suspected perforated peptic ulcer disease."],"references":["Chung KT, Shelat VG. Perforated peptic ulcer - an update. World J Gastrointest Surg. 2017 Jan 27;9(1):1-12. doi: 10.4240/wjgs.v9.i1.1. PMID: 28138363; PMCID: PMC5237817."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38295"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2725"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17595"},{"type":"media","id":"17596"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17595"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5e7c5552-ce51-4679-878f-38ec31949f31.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5e7c5552-ce51-